{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f59546fc-7342-40a6-a459-bcee4d16c194","content":"Here's a step-by-step approach:\n\n**1. Get a shell into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` inside the container:**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect the trace (CPU profiling profile):**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n**5. Copy the trace file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet` CLI isn't on PATH in the container, look for it under `C:\\Program Files\\dotnet`.\n- If you can't install tools (read-only filesystem), use the **sidecar approach**: run a debug container with the tools pre-installed sharing the same process namespace (`shareProcessNamespace: true` in the pod spec).\n- For a lighter-weight alternative, grab a dump instead: `dotnet-dump collect -p <PID>`, then analyze offline with `dotnet-dump analyze`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"61e736c2-2baa-490d-8703-6105e735b898","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advisory question, not a code task. I'll provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":393},"id":"249f63d7-1b77-411d-9b06-1b1fb9c9b8d5","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:48:20.042Z","parentId":"8f1b71e0-6813-4534-9a55-79a3d5cb4b81"}
